React 19 focuses on "Actions"—a new way to handle asynchronous data mutations—and automating manual optimizations like memoization. [1, 2] 
## 1. The "Actions" API & Form Hooks
React 19 introduces Actions to simplify handling async transitions, specifically for forms. They automatically manage pending states, error handling, and sequential requests. [3, 4, 5, 6, 7] 

* useActionState: Replaces the experimental useFormState. It manages the state of an action (pending, success, or error) and returns the current state and a wrapped action to use in your form.
* useFormStatus: Allows nested child components (like a submit button) to access the parent form's status without prop drilling.
* useOptimistic: Lets you update the UI immediately with an "expected" result while an async request is still processing, then reverts if it fails. [1, 5, 8, 9, 10] 

## 2. The React Compiler
A major "behind-the-scenes" change is the [React Compiler](https://react.dev/learn/react-compiler) (formerly "React Forget"). It automatically handles memoization, potentially eliminating the need for manual useMemo, useCallback, and React.memo by determining where optimizations are needed at compile-time. [2, 11, 12, 13, 14] 
## 3. New use API
The new use hook can read the value of a resource—like a Promise or Context—directly within the render function. [15, 16] 

* Unlike other hooks, use can be called inside loops and conditional statements.
* It simplifies data fetching by allowing you to pass a fetch Promise directly into a component, which then suspends until the data is ready. [17, 18, 19] 

## 4. Direct DX (Developer Experience) Improvements [20, 21, 22] 

* Ref as a Prop: You can now pass ref as a regular prop to functional components, making forwardRef mostly obsolete.
* Document Metadata: Built-in support for <title>, <meta>, and <link> tags anywhere in the component tree. React automatically hoists them to the document <head>.
* Simplified Context: You can now use <Context> directly instead of <Context.Provider>.
* Asset Loading: Enhanced support for preloading resources (fonts, scripts, and styles) to improve performance and prevent "layout shifts". [1, 15, 18, 23, 24, 25, 26] 

## 5. Server Components & Server Actions
While already popular in frameworks like Next.js, [Server Components](https://react.dev/reference/rsc/server-components) and Server Actions (async functions executed on the server) are now officially stable in React 19. [7, 16, 27] 
